ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach solves the candy distribution problem through iterative refinement. The intuition is simple: start with the most basic fair distribution (every child gets 1 candy), then repeatedly fix violations until all constraints are satisfied. This works because each fix brings us closer to a valid solution, and since we only increase candies (never decrease), we eventually reach a stable state. The algorithm begins by initializing a candy array with all 1s. Then it enters a loop where it scans the entire array, checking each child against both neighbors. If a child has a higher rating than a neighbor but fewer or equal candies, we increase that child's candies to be one more than the neighbor. This process repeats until a complete scan finds no violations. The time complexity is O(n²) in worst case because in pathological cases (like strictly increasing ratings), each child might need multiple adjustments that cascade through the array. Space complexity is O(n) for storing the candy array. This connects to L1 as the main driver that repeatedly calls the violation-checking scan. Common mistakes include forgetting to check both left and right neighbors, not using a while loop for multiple passes, or incorrectly handling edge cases (first and last children). The real pattern involves careful neighbor comparisons with boundary checks.

Pseudocode:
function distributeCandies(ratings):
    n = length(ratings)
    candies = [1] * n
    changed = True

    while changed:
        changed = False
        for i from 0 to n-1:
            # Check left neighbor
            if i > 0 and ratings[i] > ratings[i-1] and candies[i] <= candies[i-1]:
                candies[i] = candies[i-1] + 1
                changed = True
            # Check right neighbor
            if i < n-1 and ratings[i] > ratings[i+1] and candies[i] <= candies[i+1]:
                candies[i] = candies[i+1] + 1
                changed = True

    return sum(candies)
